>Description:
Certain key combinations turn on Overwrite mode.

(I suspect Esc-o is the one I keep hitting,
but maybe I just don't know where the "Insert"
key is on my keyboard.)

Anyway, eventually I notice that I've typed
over a bunch of text, and I see the mode 
indicator in the bottom of the DrScheme 
window that says "Overwrite"... but what I 
don't see is how to turn Overwrite off.

(I have seen students in this predicament
in the past; while one might say that this provides
the students with motivation to explore
the interface and find out about the key-bindings
list, I would argue that a frustrated student is
more likely to close DrScheme and re-open it to
try to solve the "problem.")

As an experienced user of DrScheme, *I* know
how to find the information I need in the 
Keybindings list (eventually), but I think
beginners should be given more direct guidance
here.

What sort of guidance could DrScheme provide
for a user in Overwrite mode?  Any of the following
would be an improvement:

1. There's no menu item directly related to 
   toggling Overwrite, so a breadth-first search
   fails the user there.  I would think adding
   a Overwrite-toggle to one of the menus would
   be a trivial change.  Or...

2. Hovering the mouse over the "Overwrite" mode
   indicator does not tell me anything, and 
   right-clicking the "Overwrite" mode 
   indicator does not tell me anything.  Either
   of these could either pop-up a help text 
   that tells me the current key-binding for
   toggling overwrite mode, or it could pop up 
   a context-menu where I could switch back to
   Insert mode with the mouse.
>How-To-Repeat:
1. Close your eyes and Esc-o "by accident"

2. Uselessly explore the DrScheme UI in an
   attempt to figure out how to switch back to
   Insert mode.
>Fix:
>Audit-Trail:
