Subject: Re: [plt-internal] Re: [plt-bug] all/9983: More UI feedback on toggling Overwrite mode
Date: Sun, 21 Dec 2008 10:25:25 -0500

 As a UI design matter, Emacs separates the modeline from the
 minibuffer.  The modeline is the line one up from the bottom (in ASCII
 displays), not the bottom line.
 
 It's true that right now, DrScheme is not built around the idea of
 having a minibuffer to flash information, so an extra "line" would
 probably be considered wasted space.
 
 You know, on my G1 (Android) when there's a status message, a little
 icon goes off on the top line, which is also the modeline (where it
 says "wifi on", "bluetooth on", etc).  You drag down the modeline, and
 you get to see the actual messages.  Analogously, you would need just
 one fixed space of icon to say "you have a status message".  Clicking
 on it could be as simple as popping up a window -- but the popup
 happens on the user's demand (when they are mentally expecting one,
 and are ready for the interruption).  But the status icon just blinks
 when there's a new status.  So the user gets a non-intrusive,
 non-modal notification, you can still have full text messages, but it
 takes up a fixed amount of space.
 
 S.
From: "Robby Findler" <robby@plt-scheme.org>
