 > The reason I think it'll be helpful is I see the following mode of
 > operation:
 >
 > When there's an alert, the alert icon (say a yellow triangle w/ a
 > black ! inside) flashes (maybe inverts color, or yellow goes red and
 > the black ! goes white) for quarter second.  (Maybe it's grey when
 > there are no alerts.)
 >
 > The user who hit Insert accidentally may or may not notice the thing,
 > so they might click on it or might not.  If they do, they're not much
 > worse off than they are now (though you can make the pop-up non-modal,
 > so they can just ignore it and keep working, which is better than
 > forcing them to make a decision).
 >
 > The user who hit Insert intentionally types and sees nothing change.
 > "Grr, let me hit it again."  They do, and let's say they still miss
 > the flash.  One hopes that at least the third time they hit it -- now
 > with all their attention focused on DrScheme, not on their task --
 > they notice the alert flash (that's why it needs to FLASH on each
 > alert, not just become and stay enabled).  Now they click, and they
 > find out what's going on.
 >
 > Plus it provides an extensible way to provide status on asynchronous
 > activities (eg, "compilation done", "download completed").  Modal
 > pop-ups are a terrible way of doing this, by definition.
 >
 > Shriram
