 Firefox has another mechanism for some alerts and warnings. When an 
 interesting event occurs (popup blocked, password entered, etc) Firefox 
 adds a panel to the top of the browsing area with a message, optional 
 context-sensitive actions (change popup blocking policy, remember the 
 password, etc), and a close button. It doesn't interrupt everything like 
 a modal dialog, but it has the dialog's virtue of context-sensitive 
 action buttons. That, together with the fact that it doesn't disappear 
 on its own, also makes it superior to minibuffer messages.
 
 When a programmer hits the Insert key in overwrite-disabled mode, 
 DrScheme should show a message panel explaining that overwrite mode is 
 disabled by default. The panel should have, in addition to the dismiss 
 button, a button for opening the preferences window at the right panel 
 to change the behavior of Insert.
 
 Check Syntax already does something similar to report syntax errors. 
 Some other places places that might benefit from this style of message 
 are the stepper and macro stepper, to report out-of-sync stepping 
 sessions, and the definitions and interactions buffers, to report open 
 bracket/paren correction. In the latter case, the message should have 
 buttons for the paren-correction preferences.
 
 --
 
 As a separate note, I also like the idea of extending DrScheme's status 
 bar with additional icons. The GC already has one. I think everyone 
 would love a little "Downloading PLaneT packages" icon that explained 
 why execution was taking longer than usual.
 
 Ryan
 
